00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I'm going to give you a quick introduction to tidymodels, orbital,

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
and then I'm going to show you how you can use it in your own R modeling workflows.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Let's get started.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.000
First up, what is orbital?

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Orbital is an incredible package.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
It was introduced at this year's PositConf.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
I'd highly encourage you to go check out the talks.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:44.000
They're now available on YouTube.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Emil Hviefelt from the tidymodels team gave that talk.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:55.000
The goal of orbital is to enable running predictions of tidymodels workflows directly inside databases.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:59.000
So what you can think of is kind of almost like a three-step process.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:06.000
First up, use the tidymodels tools that you're familiar with to create an R model.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:14.000
You can use tools like Recipes, Parsnip to create that model, and then use orbital.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And what orbital does is it takes all the steps of that tidymodel and converts it into SQL

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
that a database like Snowflake can understand.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:31.000
You can then use Snowflake, use any other database to either run the predictions of that model,

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
or you can actually use that SQL to then actually deploy the model directly to Snowflake

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:45.000
or any other database as a native object.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Just a quick refresher for those of you who aren't familiar with workflows

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
or maybe haven't used it in a while.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Workflows is a part of the tidymodels package, tidymodels universe.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.000
And what it lets you do is bundle together your data pre-processing steps,

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
your modeling steps, and post-processing steps into one R object.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.000
So you can combine all the things that are needed to run your model,

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:18.000
that can feature engineering, model fitting, post-processing, into a single portable R object.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:25.000
And the secret sauce of orbital is that it does that conversion over the entire workflow object.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
So it'll convert all of your feature engineering steps.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
It'll convert your model fitting steps.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
It'll convert basically anything that you can fit into workflows.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:43.000
You can put into orbital, and then that'll turn it into SQL that can be then run on a database.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.000
You might be asking yourself, why would I use orbital?

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:53.000
Why would I want to put my model fitting into a database?

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Number one, putting your model fitting in your database allows you to share your models with anyone super easily.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Because you're taking these models, converting them to SQL,

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:08.000
what you're doing is you're putting them into a language that your database can understand,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.000
and you're putting them into a language that basically almost anyone can access.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:16.000
So if you can take that model, you can take your model, turn it using orbital into SQL,

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:22.000
deploy it onto Snowflake, anyone else on your team, whether they're using something like Python,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.000
or whether they're using something that doesn't use code at all,

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:32.000
something like Power BI, can now access the outputs of your model.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
And number two, probably most importantly, it makes your model really, really, really, really, really fast.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
One of the really cool things about databases is they have a ton of compute power behind them.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
They're really good at doing things like feature engineering, like data preprocessing.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And especially because your data is already there,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:59.000
one of the things that fitting your models directly in the databases does is it removes the step of having to download data onto a different machine,

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
download it onto an R machine.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Instead, the model fitting can be done directly in the database, which tends to make that make the model fitting incredibly fast.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:17.000
And we'll go over that just a little bit.

